{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8bfeb99d-175e-4e25-8a53-a6521a80a3c9","content":"This is a common macOS issue. The .NET Android build tooling has **its own JDK discovery logic** and often doesn't reliably pick up `JAVA_HOME` — especially when building from an IDE (VS Code, Rider) which may not inherit your shell environment.\n\n**Recommended fixes (pick one):**\n\n**Option A — Use the Microsoft OpenJDK bundled with the workload** (preferred):\n```bash\ndotnet workload repair\n```\nThis ensures the bundled Microsoft OpenJDK 17 is installed. The build system finds it automatically.\n\n**Option B — Explicitly tell MSBuild where your Temurin JDK is:**\n\nAdd this to your `.csproj`:\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup Condition=\"$([MSBuild]::IsOSPlatform('osx'))\">\n  <JavaSdkDirectory>/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home</JavaSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nVerify the path matches your install:\n```bash\n/usr/libexec/java_home -v 17\n```\n\n**Option C — Make JAVA_HOME visible system-wide** (so IDEs see it):\n```bash\nsudo launchctl setenv JAVA_HOME \"$(/usr/libexec/java_home -v 17)\"\n```\nThen restart your IDE.\n\n**Option A** is the path of least resistance — the Android workload ships its own JDK 17 specifically to avoid these issues.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2f0571d8-a6b4-4025-89da-da6d0f52683b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure with a Java-related error on macOS. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed with JAVA_HOME pointing to it.\n\nLet me think about what common issues exist with .NET MAUI Android builds and Java on macOS.\n\nThe most common issue here is that .NET MAUI / Android SDK has specific Java version requirements. Let me recall:\n\n- .NET 8 MAUI requires JDK 17\n- .NET 9 MAUI also requires JDK 17\n\nBut there's a well-known issue: the .NET Android build tooling looks for Java in a specific location and may not respect JAVA_HOME in all cases, OR there's the issue where the build tooling bundles its own JDK.\n\n\nActually, the real culprit on macOS is usually that .NET MAUI's Android workload installs its own Microsoft OpenJDK distribution, and when JAVA_HOME points elsewhere, it can cause version mismatches or path resolution issues. The user has JDK 17 which meets the version requirement, but the Android SDK on macOS might not be finding or using it correctly.\n\nThe build system uses a specific property to locate Java rather than always relying on JAVA_HOME, and when using Adoptium Temurin, the JDK ends up in a non-standard location like `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home` that the MAUI build tools might not automatically discover. On macOS specifically, the Temurin JDK installs to a path that MSBuild might not pick up automatically, or .NET MAUI's bundled Microsoft OpenJDK could be conflicting with an external installation. The fix usually involves either using the Microsoft OpenJDK from the Android workload or explicitly setting `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` in the project file. Though I'm also wondering if this could be a version mismatch—.NET 9 still targets JDK 17, but there might be edge cases where the build tools expect something different. /temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`, or I could use `/usr/libexec/java_home -v 17` to automatically get the right path.\n\nSince `java -version` works for them, their PATH is set up correctly, but the real issue is likely that .NET MAUI's Android build process isn't picking up the Temurin JDK properly on macOS—the build system looks in specific locations and the `JAVA_HOME` variable might not be reaching the MSBuild process when building from an IDE. The fix is probably to explicitly set `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` in the project configuration.\n\nActually, thinking about this more carefully—the most common Java-related MAUI Android build failures are about the SDK not being found or version mismatches. For .NET 8 and 9, MAUI bundles its own Microsoft OpenJDK 17 with the Android workload, and the build system prefers that. Problems typically happen when the workload isn't fully installed, `JAVA_HOME` points to an incompatible version, or on macOS the path resolution fails. Since they're specifically using Adoptium Temurin, that might be the source of the conflict. Temurin 17.0.12 came out in July 2024, and there have been some reported compatibility issues between certain JDK distributions and Android build tools, especially with the `d8` and `r8` compilers. I think the most practical approach is to recommend using the bundled Microsoft OpenJDK that ships with the .NET MAUI Android workload, explicitly setting the `JavaSdkDirectory` in the project file if needed, and running `dotnet workload repair` to ensure everything's properly installed.\n\nSince I can't access the repository context here, I'm treating this as a general knowledge question. The most common culprit on macOS is that the Android SDK has trouble locating JDKs outside the Microsoft OpenJDK distribution, so the fix typically involves either installing that specific version or configuring the path explicitly in the project settings. On macOS specifically, the IDE often doesn't inherit `JAVA_HOME` from the shell profile even though the terminal can find Java, so the build fails when triggered from the IDE. I could set it system-wide with `launchctl`, configure it in the project file, or launch the IDE from the terminal. But if they're building from the command line with `dotnet build`, that wouldn't be the issue. Without seeing the actual error, I should probably cover the most common causes. The .NET Android tooling doesn't necessarily respect the system JAVA_HOME, so I should recommend either using the Microsoft OpenJDK that comes with the Android workload or explicitly configuring the JavaSdkDirectory property in the project file to point to the Temurin installation. This is a straightforward .NET MAUI question, so I can give a direct answer without needing to dig deeper.","outputTokens":3254,"requestId":"9814:23E21D:160A18B:18973A9:6A051E2E"},"id":"965d9bc1-fa9b-42e3-a427-e17374c2a846","timestamp":"2026-05-14T00:59:24.438Z","parentId":"3addc1a9-d204-49d3-809b-285cebd23b07"}
